<p>However, what you are trying to do is pretty simple.  There are two pretty simple ways to keep track how long some amount of code has been running:</p>
<p>User a Timer object from Wpilib, or knowing that the robot code executes in a loop, just count how many times youâ€™ve looped and to get the number of seconds just divide by the loop frequency.  The default robot loop is 50Hz, or fifty times a second.  With a little math you can figure out that 1 second / 50 = .02 (or 20 milliseconds).  If you had a loop counter, and wanted it to run for 4 seconds, you would run your code until the counter says 200.</p>
<p>The timer example is easy too:</p>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">public class MyRobot extends TimedRobot{
    Timer m_auto_timer;
    public void autonomousInit(){
        m_auto_timer = new Timer();
        m_auto_timer.start()
    }

    public void autonomousPeriodic(){
        if(!m_auto_timer.hasElapsed(4)){
            // This means we haven't run for 4 seconds yet
            &lt; run the code you want to run &gt;
        } else{
            &lt;stop running the code you ran before&gt;
        }
}
</code></pre>
